<subsection xml:id="subsec-area-of-sectors" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Area of Sectors</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_87rou6qs">
            <p xml:id="auto_66g0o9ec">
            <dl>
                <li xml:id="auto_axskw85z">
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_j12fd1hu">
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_n5l67jvd">
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_eoehm87l">
                        2.6 Area of a Part of a Circle
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_w90bwyo4">
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_ii4nl7e8">
                        Work out the area of a sector of a circle in real-life situations
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_jo50nrc3" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_41zhdo5i">
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_iql58e8o" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_tahyn07k">
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_c9qzyzvu" component="lesson-plan">
                <p xml:id="auto_4fp8hcn9"> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li xml:id="auto_tr8ye69m">
                        <p xml:id="auto_6l161ta8">
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Define what a sector is (minor and major) and identify the components of the sector area formula.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_lerk9bk5">
                        <p xml:id="auto_rfow0j70">
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Calculate the area of a sector using the formula <m>\frac{\theta}{360} \times \pi r^2</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_3grwd7wm">
                        <p xml:id="auto_sneo5ccw">
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Solve real-life problems involving areas of sectors, such as windscreen wipers and grazing areas.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
    <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p xml:id="auto_979qktlg">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/area-of-a-part-of-a-circle/area-of-sectors.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_5cw4le4x">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/area-of-a-part-of-a-circle/step-by-step-guide_area-of-sectors.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 1: Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_1ove8sf5">
            <alert>Expected Time:</alert> 15 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_hzecys6o">
            <alert>Grouping:</alert> Work in groups
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_uxtmgxxb">
            <alert>Teacher Questions During Discovery:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_yafrcfms">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_9b202u12">
                    <p xml:id="auto_0rzcisuc"><q>What is a sector?</q></p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_bc5nztq3">
                    <p xml:id="auto_6zexs0om"><q>What fraction of the circle is this sector?</q></p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_db9r0uno">
                    <p xml:id="auto_haes43w6"><q>How did you calculate the area of the sector?</q></p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_yzn5odm3">
                    <p xml:id="auto_550pufwt"><q>What is the relationship between the angle and the area?</q></p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_n7t8qfdo">
                    <p xml:id="auto_nhsgk1i8"><q>Did different groups get the same formula?</q></p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_f3vl6sqv">
            <alert>Teacher Role:</alert> Circulate among groups, ensuring learners understand how to measure the angle and cut the sector accurately. For struggling groups, prompt: <q>Let us start by finding the area of the whole circle. What fraction of <m>360^\circ</m> is <m>30^\circ</m>? Now multiply the fraction by the area of the circle.</q> For early finishers: <q>Can you write a general formula for finding the area of any sector?</q> Identify 2–3 groups with clear findings to share with the class.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_j0o61lh0">
            <alert>Expected Responses:</alert> The area of a sector equals the fraction (angle/360) times the area of the circle.
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <activity xml:id="auto_jgru7mkz">
        <p xml:id="auto_8g8frzif">
            <m>\textbf{Work in groups}</m>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_k7kccgf1">
            <term>What you require:</term>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_m2wf2oxq">
            A graph paper and a razorblade or a pair of scissor✂️
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_aywlhlln">
            <ol xml:id="auto_8yrn1lcs" marker="(i)">
                <li xml:id="auto_tht48yko">
                    <p xml:id="auto_6kaxywve">
                        Draw a circle of radius <m>7 \, cm</m> on a graph paper.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_4vra5tnz">Cut out the circle along its boundary.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_iej9c8o8">Mark the centre of the circle.</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_eg0a5xax">
                    <p xml:id="auto_bz8wktyl">
                        Measure an angle of <m>30^\circ</m> at the centre and cut 
                        out as shown.
                    </p>
                    <image width="60%">
                    <latex-image label="sector2">
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                            % Draw the first shape (Sector inside the larger circle)
                            \draw[thick] (0,0) circle (2);
                            \fill[blue!20] (0,0) -- (30:2) arc (30:150:2) -- cycle;
                            \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (30:2);
                            \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (150:2);
                            \draw[thick] (30:2) ;
                            \node at (0,0.5) {$30^\circ$};
                            
                            
                            % Arrow pointing to the second shape
                            \draw[-&gt;, very thick] (2.5,0) -- (4.5,0);
                            
                            % Draw the second shape (sector facing right, matching the larger one)
                            \begin{scope}[shift={(6,0)}, rotate=360]
                                \fill[blue!20] (0,0) -- (30:1.5) arc (30:150:1.5) -- cycle;
                                \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (30:1.5);
                                \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (150:1.5);
                                \draw[thick] (30:1.5) arc (30:150:1.5);
                                \node at (0,0.5) {$30^\circ$};
                                
                            \end{scope}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>

                    </image>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_nmab4q2m">
                    <p xml:id="auto_4i12j5yg">
                        Estimate the area by counting the number of squares enclosed by the arc and the 
                        two radii of the circle.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ea32ihc2">Express the angle of the sector (<m>30^\circ</m>) 
                as a fraction of the angle at the centre of the circle (<m>360^\circ</m>).</li>
                <li xml:id="auto_t7vbcvfd">
                    <p xml:id="auto_17taq25m">
                        Multiply the fraction obtained in (6) by the area of the circle.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_tvtufm32">
                    <p xml:id="auto_sp5o0l97">
                        Discuss and share the result with other groups.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        
    </activity>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 2: Structured Instruction</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_efn4007s">
            <alert>Expected Time:</alert> 10 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_twpp49th">
            <alert>Scaffolding Strategies to Address Misconceptions:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_r8nc9mdj">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_nnm2p9fq">
                    <p xml:id="auto_nyvzwxju"><alert>Misconception:</alert> <q>I can use the angle directly without dividing by 360.</q> <alert>Clarification:</alert> You must express the angle as a fraction of <m>360^\circ</m> first.</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_dq8a0z1f">
                    <p xml:id="auto_p5g8tcvr"><alert>Misconception:</alert> <q>The formula works for any angle unit.</q> <alert>Clarification:</alert> The angle must be in degrees. If given in radians, convert first or use a different formula.</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_f7ji6px3">
                    <p xml:id="auto_0vfceyit"><alert>Misconception:</alert> <q>A sector is the same as a segment.</q> <alert>Clarification:</alert> A sector is bounded by two radii and an arc, while a segment is the region between a chord and an arc.</p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_wam1tr6u">
                    <p xml:id="auto_0h8k8tjn"><alert>Misconception:</alert> <q>I can use diameter instead of radius.</q> <alert>Clarification:</alert> The formula uses radius. If given diameter, divide by 2 first.</p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <p xml:id="auto_dxkpsrfz">
        <m>\textbf{Key Takeaway}</m>
    </p>
    
    <p xml:id="auto_hnpbn8dv">
        A <m>\textbf{sector}</m> is a region bounded by two radii and an arc.
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_yfzk880n">
        <term>Minor sector</term> is one whose area is less than a half of the area of the circle.
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_gkwpw70i">
        <term>Major sector</term> is onewhose area is greater than a half of the 
        area of the circle.
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_sve1kqni">
        See the figure below;
    </p>
    <image width="80%">
    <latex-image label="Sector">
        \begin{tikzpicture}
            % Draw the circle
            \draw[very thick] (0,0) circle(2cm);

            % Define sector angles
            \fill[pattern=north east lines] (0,0) -- (30:2cm) arc (30:150:2cm) -- cycle;

            % Draw sector boundaries
            \draw[very thick] (0,0) -- (30:2cm);
            \draw[very thick] (0,0) -- (150:2cm);
            
            % Label the center
            \node[circle,fill=black,inner sep=1.5pt,label=below:$O$] at (0,0) {};
            
            % Label the minor and major sectors
            \node[right] at (3,-1) {\textbf{Major sector}};
            \node[above] at (0,3) {\textbf{Minor sector}};
            
            % Guide lines to labels
            \draw[-&gt;] (1,-1) -- (3,-1);
            \draw[-&gt;] (0,1) -- (0,3);
        \end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
        
    </image>
        
    <p xml:id="auto_0c5uwj6v">
        <term>The Area of a Sector</term>
    </p>
    
    <p xml:id="auto_j40v4f6t">
        <md>
            <mrow> \text{Area of a Sector}=\amp \frac{\theta}{360} \times  \pi r^2</mrow>
        </md>
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_kgzr7gy4">
        where:
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_mbf2gigq">
        <ul xml:id="auto_qvfb8ln6">
            <li xml:id="auto_l2638y88">
                <p xml:id="auto_vspfbr93">
                    <m>\theta</m> is in degrees,
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_4l1p71bd">
                <p xml:id="auto_oqrtapbr">
                    <m>r</m> is the radius of the circle,
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_wpib4x6f">
                <p xml:id="auto_di6a1zio">
                    <m>\pi \,≈ \,3.142\, \text{or} \, \frac{22}{7}.</m>
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_on5b1foo">
            <alert>Expected Time:</alert> 10 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_hd68hy91">
            <alert>Objective:</alert> Learners apply the sector formula to solve varied problems, moving from straightforward calculations to composite shapes.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_xpd874bz">
            <alert>Teacher's Role:</alert> Work through the first example on the board step by step. Allow learners to attempt subsequent examples in pairs. Circulate and provide support as needed.
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <example xml:id="auto_n6brwyrx">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_yqhc6ujz">
                Find the area of a sector of a circle of 
                radius <m>7 \,cm</m> if the angle subtended at the 
                centre is <m> 90^\circ</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_ghwxcalj">
                The values given are, <m>\theta=90^\circ \, , \, r= 7\,cm</m>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_42c6jjfm">
                <m>\text{Area}= \frac{\theta}{360} \times \pi r^2</m>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_irhw8e26">
                <md>
                    <mrow> \text{Area}=\amp \frac{90}{360} \times \frac{22}{7} \times  ( 7^2)</mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp \frac{1}{4} \times \frac{22}{7} \times 49 </mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp \frac{1}{4} \times 22 \times 7</mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp  38.5 \,cm^2</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example xml:id="auto_nol4w75f">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_gmv9muhc">
                Find the area of a sector of a circle shown below;(use <m>\pi=3.142</m>) 
                
            </p>
            <image width="60%">
            <latex-image label="sector3">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    % Draw the circle
                    \draw[very thick] (0,0) circle (3cm);

                    % Draw the sector
                    \fill[blue!45] (0,0) -- (3,0) arc [start angle=0, end angle=45, radius=3cm] -- cycle;

                    % Draw the radius lines
                    \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (3,0);
                    \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (3*0.707,3*0.707); % 3*cos(45), 3*sin(45)

                    % Label the angle
                    \draw [very thick](1,0) arc [start angle=0, end angle=45, radius=1cm];
                    \node at (1.3,0.4) { $45^\circ$};

                    % Label the radius
                    \node at (1.5,-0.3) {\textbf{ $10$ cm}};
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
                
                
            </image>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_idhgk14p">
                The values given are, <m>\theta=45^\circ \, , \, r= 10\,cm</m>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_mvjzhemh">
                <m>\text{Area}= \frac{\theta}{360} \times \pi r^2</m>
            </p>
             <p xml:id="auto_mr71cxh3">
                <md>
                    <mrow> \text{Area}\amp \frac{45}{360} \times 3.142 \times  ( 10^2)</mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp \frac{1}{8} \times 3.142 \times 100 </mrow>
                    
                    <mrow> =\amp  39.275 \,cm^2</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example xml:id="auto_bv7bpxic">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_q2wsh3gf">
                The shaded region in the figure
                below shows the area swept out on a
                flat windscreen by a wiper.
                Calculate the area of this region.
            </p>
            <image width="60%">
            <latex-image label="sector4">
                \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.5]
                    % Sector (area swept by wiper)
                    \fill[pattern=north east lines] (0,0) -- (100:16) arc (100:0:16) -- cycle;
                    
                    \fill[fill=white,very thick] (0,0) -- (100:14) arc (100:0:14) -- cycle;
                    
                    \fill[fill=blue] (0,0) -- (100:1) arc (100:0:1) -- cycle;

                    

                    % Lines for sector
                    \draw [very thick] (0,0) -- (100:16);
                    \draw [very thick] (0,0) -- (0:16);
                    \draw  [very thick] (100:16) arc (100:0:16);

                    % Angle label
                    \node [right] at (0.9, 0.8) {$120^\circ$};
                    \draw[&lt;-&gt;,below,blue,very thick] (0,-0.2)--(14,-0.2);
                    \draw[&lt;-&gt;,below,blue,very thick] (14,-0.2)--(16,-0.2);

                    % Length labels
                    \node[below] at (0:9) {16 cm};
                    \node[above left] at (100:14.5) {4 cm};

                    % Wiper label
                    \node[left] at (100:16) {Wiper};
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
                
                
            </image>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_t420z4h7">
                The area of the rigion is goten by subtracting the <m>\textbf{Area of the smaller sector}</m> 
                from <m>\textbf{Area of the larger sector}</m> .
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_viwzx8ho">
                Use <m>\text{Area}= \frac{\theta}{360} \times \pi r^2</m>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_hg3xdmjh">
                <m>\textbf{Area of the larger sector}</m> 
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_fz7ngep5">
                <md>
                    <mrow>R= \amp 16\,cm + 4\,cm </mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp 20\,cm </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_s8j4qhg0">
                <md>
                    <mrow>\theta= \amp 120^\circ </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_8cnkrxye">
                <md>
                    <mrow> A=\amp \frac{120}{360} \times \frac{22}{7} \times  20^2 </mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp \frac{1}{3} \times \frac{22}{7} \times 400</mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp 419.047619  \,cm^2 </mrow>
                    
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_d6iiiajk">
                <m>\textbf{Area of the smaller sector}</m> 
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_gfng1f4y">
                <md>
                    <mrow>r= \amp 16\,cm  </mrow>
                    
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_0of0cd63">
                <md>
                    <mrow>\theta= \amp 120^\circ </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_ctm4m9u8">
                <md>
                    <mrow> A=\amp \frac{120}{360} \times \frac{22}{7} \times  16^2 </mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp \frac{1}{3} \times \frac{22}{7} \times 256</mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp 268.19047 \,cm^2</mrow>
                    
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_4rywkhoe">
                Therefore,
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_oc2jc8bs">
                <md>
                    <mrow> \text{Area of the region}=\amp \textbf{Area of the larger sector} -\textbf{Area of the smaller sector}</mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp 419.047619 \,cm^2- 268.19047  \,cm^2</mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp 150.85714\,cm^2 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
<axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 4: Assessment — Exit Ticket</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_8ifbytva">
            <alert>Expected Time:</alert> 5 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_xfb73b7n">
            <alert>Instructions:</alert> Learners complete the exercises individually. Collect responses as an exit ticket.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_nnfqbtlo">
            <alert>Answer Key (Teacher Reference):</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_bm79efte">
            <ol marker="1.">
                <li xml:id="auto_hu6vvdyd">
                    <p xml:id="auto_zjc0evfv">
                        <ol marker="(a)">
                            <li xml:id="auto_jnqqgdjh"><p xml:id="auto_hweda95h"><m>A = \frac{264}{360} \times \frac{22}{7} \times 10^2 \approx 230.48 \,m^2</m></p></li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_dh2kdyf3"><p xml:id="auto_84wfw3yq"><m>A = \frac{40}{360} \times \frac{22}{7} \times 8.4^2 \approx 24.64 \,cm^2</m></p></li>
                            <li xml:id="auto_2a6ora90"><p xml:id="auto_ffcd8mnn"><m>A = \frac{80}{360} \times \frac{22}{7} \times 1.4^2 \approx 1.37 \,cm^2</m></p></li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_egbm4oov"><p xml:id="auto_na959l26">Use <m>A = \frac{\theta}{360} \times \pi r^2</m> and solve for <m>r</m>.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_x12cfw1o"><p xml:id="auto_d6bszrcu">Grazing area is a quarter circle: <m>A = \frac{90}{360} \times \frac{22}{7} \times 21^2 = 346.5\,m^2</m>.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_2csf0tjk"><p xml:id="auto_z33slec6"><m>18\pi = \frac{45}{360} \times \pi x^2 \Rightarrow x^2 = 144 \Rightarrow x = 12\,cm</m>.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_hszl5174"><p xml:id="auto_wfnlow76">For radians: <m>A = \frac{1}{2}r^2\theta = \frac{1}{2} \times 64 \times \frac{\pi}{3} \approx 33.51\,cm^2</m>.</p></li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </axiom>
    

    <exercises>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A sector of a circle of radius <m>r</m>is
                    subtended at the centre by an angle
                    of <m>\theta</m>. Calculate the area of the sector
                    if:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(i)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                 <m>r=10\,m ,\quad \theta=264^\circ</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                               <m>r=8.4\,cm ,\quad \theta=40^\circ</m> 
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>r=1.4\,cm ,\quad \theta=80^\circ</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(i)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                               <m>230.4 \;\text{m}^2</m> 
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>24.63 \;\text{cm}^2</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>1.37 \;\text{cm}^2</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    The area of a sector of a circle is <m>154 \,cm^2</m>
                    . Find the radius of the circle if the
                    angle subtended at the centre is <m>140^\circ</m>. (Take <m>\pi= \frac{22}{7}</m>)
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>11.22</m> cm
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A goat is tethered at the corner of a
                    fenced rectangular grazing field. If
                    the length of the rope is <m>21 \,m</m>, what
                    is its grazing area?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>346.3 \;\text{m}^2</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Shown below is a sector of a circle, with radius <m>x\,cm</m> 
                </p>
                <image width="60%">
                <latex-image label="sector5">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                         % Define the radius and angle
                        \def\angle{80} % Angle of the sector
                        \def\radius{3} % Arbitrary length for visualization

                        % Draw the sector
                        \draw[thick] (0,0) -- (\angle:\radius) arc (\angle:0:\radius) -- cycle;

                        % Draw the angle arc
                        \draw[thick] (10:0.8) arc (10:\angle-10:0.8);

                        % Label the angle
                        \node[above] at (22:\radius/3) {\Large $45^\circ$};

                        % Label the radius
                        \node at (\angle+15:\radius-0.5) {\Large $x$};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                    
                </image>
                <p>
                  The area of the sector is <m>18 \pi \,cm^2</m>. Find the length of <m>x</m>?  
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>12</m> cm
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
           <statement>
            <p>
                A sector has an angle of <m>\frac{\pi}{3}</m> radians and a radius of <m>8 \,cm</m>. Find its area.
            </p>
           </statement> 
           <answer>
            <p>
                <m>33.5 \;\text{cm}^2</m>
            </p>
           </answer>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

            <exercise  label="ex-determining-the-angle-of-a-sector">
                <stack label="stk-determining-the-angle-of-a-sector" source="stack/top/2-0-Measurement-Geometry/2-6-Area-of-a-Part-of-a-Circle/2-6-2-Area-of-a-Sector-of-a-Circle/Determining-the-Angle-of-a-Sector-.xml" />
            </exercise>
                

            <exercise  label="ex-calculating-the-area-of-a-sector">
                <stack label="stk-calculating-the-area-of-a-sector" source="stack/top/2-0-Measurement-Geometry/2-6-Area-of-a-Part-of-a-Circle/2-6-2-Area-of-a-Sector-of-a-Circle/Calculating-the-area-of-a-sector.xml" />
            </exercise>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_w6c0zhmf">
            <alert>Struggling Learners:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_el544u75">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_w6jjgziw"><p xml:id="auto_cpyrpl3o">Provide pre-drawn circles with sectors already outlined.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_a7j82b7q"><p xml:id="auto_7lxunkd6">Use simpler angles (e.g., <m>90^\circ</m>, <m>180^\circ</m>) for initial practice.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_8ybep1w3"><p xml:id="auto_kgr4ejux">Pair struggling learners with confident problem solvers.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_vsgogmb8"><p xml:id="auto_0afq5nck">Provide step-by-step calculation templates.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_jdcxdcfi"><p xml:id="auto_aqbbg4lj">Break down the formula into steps: find the fraction, find the area of the circle, multiply.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_l18yc9a9"><p xml:id="auto_p0vno4h9">Allow use of calculators.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_mnyfrg5a">
            <alert>On-Level Learners:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_heha0q96">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_f8kl8ewo"><p xml:id="auto_hyr9y0nq">Encourage learners to verify their formula with different angles.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_dvk2e3lv"><p xml:id="auto_k3f4rzum">Ask learners to explain the relationship between the angle and the area.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_vmgqdq46"><p xml:id="auto_fukr0siw">Provide mixed practice with different types of sector problems.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_5s0jclfr"><p xml:id="auto_spwvmglm">Challenge learners to solve problems involving major sectors.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_zedvvak9">
            <alert>Advanced Learners:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_1lyzzmgz">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_dnoeelhl"><p xml:id="auto_5d0u41yo">Challenge learners to derive the formula for sectors in radians.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_bj5aekgo"><p xml:id="auto_degumk8k">Investigate the relationship between sector area and arc length.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_q1dad8lb"><p xml:id="auto_m2edzi5t">Solve optimisation problems: Given a fixed radius, what angle maximises the sector area?</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_9nh56e9g"><p xml:id="auto_xnfr5l3u">Apply the concept to composite shapes involving multiple sectors.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_qlnwkw7m">
            <alert>Extension Activity — Pizza Slice Design Project:</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_qn4dtjoz">
            A pizza restaurant wants to design different slice sizes. Tasks:
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li xml:id="auto_eml8nkjk"><p xml:id="auto_6g45od0l">Design a circular pizza with radius <m>30</m> cm.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_jhvgcr31"><p xml:id="auto_cjqya68t">Calculate the area of one slice if the pizza is cut into 8 equal slices.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_c99j2whz"><p xml:id="auto_alklesxb">Calculate the area of one slice if the pizza is cut into 6 equal slices.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_xai96mfm"><p xml:id="auto_v9vtxk9n">If a customer wants a slice of <m>50\,cm^2</m>, what angle should the slice have?</p></li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </axiom>

